            ContentJson = """{"passingScore":80,"questionsPerQuiz":8,"shuffleOptions":true,"showExplanationsAfterSubmit":true,"questions":[{"id":"sf1","text":"You're setting up a new shop floor kiosk. After opening the display, what is the primary way workers authenticate to perform actions?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"They log in with their email and password through the standard login page"},{"id":"b","text":"They scan their RFID badge or barcode and enter their numeric PIN","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"An admin logs them in from the admin panel"},{"id":"d","text":"They use a shared kiosk password posted on the wall"}],"explanation":"The shop floor signs you in one action at a time. Scan your badge or barcode, then type your number PIN (at least 4 digits). You're signed out automatically once the action is done. You can also tap your name card and type your full password instead."},{"id":"sf2","text":"A worker scans their badge at the shop floor kiosk but walks away without entering their PIN. What happens after 20 seconds?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The system sends a notification to the worker's phone"},{"id":"b","text":"The PIN overlay stays open indefinitely until someone cancels it"},{"id":"c","text":"The PIN overlay auto-cancels and the display returns to the main dashboard","isCorrect":true},{"id":"d","text":"The worker is automatically clocked out"}],"explanation":"The PIN box closes on its own after about 20 seconds. If the worker doesn't submit in time, it cancels and the display goes back to the main screen. This keeps a forgotten box from blocking the kiosk for the next person."},{"id":"sf3","text":"On the worker card grid, what does a yellow left stripe on a worker's card indicate?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The worker is currently working on a job"},{"id":"b","text":"The worker is on break or lunch","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The worker is clocked out for the day"},{"id":"d","text":"The worker has an overdue job assignment"}],"explanation":"The colored edge shows the worker's clock status: green means working, yellow means on break or lunch, and gray means clocked out."},{"id":"sf4","text":"A worker clocks in but has no assigned jobs. What happens next on the shop floor display?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Nothing — the worker sees the standard actions overlay and can log out"},{"id":"b","text":"A job picker overlay appears automatically, showing unassigned jobs the worker can select","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The worker is redirected to the kanban board to find a job"},{"id":"d","text":"An alert is sent to the manager to assign a job"}],"explanation":"After clocking in, if the worker has no jobs, a job picker opens on its own a moment later. The worker can pick an unassigned job or skip. The picker closes by itself after about 15 seconds."},{"id":"sf5","text":"How do you assign an unassigned job to a worker directly from the shop floor main dashboard (without authenticating)?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Click the unassigned job, then click the worker's name from a dropdown"},{"id":"b","text":"Drag the unassigned job card from the unassigned section and drop it onto the worker's card","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Right-click the job and select 'Assign To'"},{"id":"d","text":"You cannot assign jobs from the main dashboard — you must authenticate first"}],"explanation":"You can drag unassigned job cards. Drag a job from the unassigned section and drop it onto any worker card in the grid. The job is assigned right away and the display refreshes. You don't need to sign in to drag and drop."},{"id":"sf6","text":"A Production Worker signs in on the shop floor kiosk. Which dock actions will they see?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Both Receive Goods and Ship Goods"},{"id":"b","text":"Receive Goods only","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Ship Goods only"},{"id":"d","text":"Neither — dock actions are only for Admin users"}],"explanation":"Receive Goods is available to Admins, Managers, Office Managers, Engineers, and Production Workers. Ship Goods is limited to Admins, Managers, and Office Managers. Both show only while the worker is clocked in."},{"id":"sf7","text":"You adjust the font size on the shop floor kiosk to 18px and switch to dark theme. The browser is restarted. What happens to these settings?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"They reset to defaults (12px, light theme)"},{"id":"b","text":"They are kept — the kiosk remembers your text size and theme","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Only the theme is preserved, font size resets"},{"id":"d","text":"They are saved to the user's account preferences on the server"}],"explanation":"Both the text size and the theme are remembered on the device, so they stay put even after the browser restarts. The kiosk keeps its look without anyone setting it up again."},{"id":"sf8","text":"When you mark a job stage to show on the shop floor, what does that control?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Whether jobs in that stage can be edited from the shop floor"},{"id":"b","text":"Whether jobs in that stage appear on the shop floor display","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Whether workers can clock in when assigned to jobs in that stage"},{"id":"d","text":"Whether the stage column is visible on the board"}],"explanation":"Marking a stage for the shop floor controls whether it appears there. Only marked stages show their jobs. This keeps office-only stages like quoting, invoicing, and payment off the floor, since they don't matter to hands-on workers."},{"id":"sf9","text":"During the receiving flow on the shop floor, a worker selects a purchase order. What can they adjust before confirming receipt?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The vendor name and PO number"},{"id":"b","text":"The quantity to receive for each line item and optionally select a bin location","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The unit price and total cost of each line"},{"id":"d","text":"The expected delivery date and carrier information"}],"explanation":"The receiving overlay shows each PO line with its remaining quantity. Workers adjust the receive quantity per line using +/- buttons (capped at the remaining quantity). They can also optionally select a bin location from a dropdown. Clicking 'Receive All' submits all lines with quantity > 0."},{"id":"sf10","text":"A worker starts a timer on a job from the shop floor actions overlay. Where does this timer show up?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Only in the Time Tracking page — the shop floor display does not show active timers"},{"id":"b","text":"On the worker's card in the main grid, as a timer mark next to the job, and the job stands out on the action screen","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Only in the header stats bar as a global timer count"},{"id":"d","text":"In a separate timer panel that slides out from the right"}],"explanation":"A running timer shows in a couple of places: the worker's card gets a timer mark next to that job, and the job stands out on the action screen. You start it and stop it from that same action screen."}]}"""
