            AppRoutes = """["/display/shop-floor/scan"]""",
            Tags = """["shop-floor","kiosk","scan","inventory"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Inventory Scan Station\n\nThe Inventory Scan Station is a barcode-first kiosk page built for warehouse and stockroom staff who work mostly with a handheld scanner: scan a part, choose what to do, confirm, repeat. There's no menu to work through — the part you scan decides which actions you're offered.\n\n### Scan to Begin\n\nThe page shows one big prompt — 'Scan a part barcode to begin' — and a scan box that's ready to go. Scan a part's barcode (or type the part number and press Enter) and it looks up that part. The header keeps a running 'Scanned' count for the session, and a **Recent Scans** list builds up below the box with each part you've looked at, its description, and its current stock — so you can see at a glance what you've been working through.\n\nWhen the part is found, the **action screen** opens. If the barcode isn't recognized, you get a 'Part not found' message and the screen closes after a moment so you can scan the next item.\n\n### The Action Screen — What You Scanned\n\nThe top of the screen confirms what you scanned: the part number, description, how much is on hand, and where it lives (when it's in one known bin). It's your quick check before you act — make sure the part and stock match what's in your hand.\n\n### The 8 Actions\n\nBelow that is a grid of large, touch-friendly buttons. Only the actions that make sense for that part right now are offered; the rest are grayed out with a short reason (for example, **Ship** is off when the part has no open shipments). The eight actions are:\n\n- **Move** — move stock from one bin to another. You pick where it's coming from, where it's going, and how much.\n- **Count** — count what's actually in a bin: type the amount you physically counted, and it records the difference from what was expected.\n- **Receive** — receive incoming stock against an open purchase order, into a bin you choose.\n- **Issue** — give material to a job: pick the job, where it's coming from, and how much you used.\n- **Ship** — fill an open shipment for this part (only on when the part has open shipments).\n- **Inspect** — run a quality check against the part's inspection checklist.\n- **Job** — when you scan a job barcode instead of a part, the screen shows that job's details and its actions.\n- **Return** — record a return against a recent shipment of this part (only on when there are recent shipments).\n\nTap an action and a short step-by-step takes over, asking only for what that action needs — quantities, bins, the job, purchase order, or shipment. Each has its own Confirm and Cancel; Cancel drops you back to the buttons without changing anything.\n\n### Multi-Scan Mode\n\nFor repeat work — receiving a pallet, moving a whole shelf — turn on **Multi-Scan** (the repeat switch at the bottom of the screen). With it on, finishing an action doesn't close the screen; it goes back to the buttons and shows 'Ready for next scan', so you can scan the next part right away. With it off (the default), the screen closes after each action and takes you back to the scan prompt. Tap **Done** anytime to close it.\n\n### The Same Screen on the Main Display\n\nYou don't have to be on the scan page to use these actions. The main shop floor display has the very same action screen built in. Scan a part barcode there and it pops up too, with the identical 8 buttons and steps. The scan page just gives stockroom staff a clean, full-screen home for this work without the worker cards around it.\n\n### What Gets Recorded\n\nEvery finished action records a movement and a log entry: the part, quantity, where it moved from and to, the related job, purchase order, or shipment, who did it, and when. That log powers both the **Daily Scan Log** (a filterable record of the day) and the **Undo** panel (which lets a supervisor back out a recent mistake). See the Field Reference for those two.","sections":[]}"""
        });

