        // ── Setting Up a Shop Floor Kiosk (Article) ──────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Setting Up a Shop Floor Kiosk",
            Slug = "shop-floor-kiosk-setup",
            Summary = "First-time terminal pairing: an admin signs in, names the terminal, picks or creates a team, and the device gets a persistent token — gating both the main display and the clock kiosk.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 7,
            AppRoutes = """["/display/shop-floor/clock","/display/shop-floor"]""",
            Tags = """["shop-floor","kiosk","setup","admin","terminal"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Setting Up a Shop Floor Kiosk\n\nBefore a shop floor display or clock kiosk can be used, the device has to be **paired** to your company and assigned to a team. This is a one-time setup an administrator does the first time the kiosk opens on a new device. After that, ordinary workers use it without ever signing in as an admin again.\n\n### When Setup Appears\n\nWhen the clock kiosk opens, it checks whether this device has been paired before. If it hasn't — a brand-new device, a cleared browser, or a terminal an admin turned off — the kiosk goes into **Setup** instead of the worker dashboard. Setup has two steps.\n\n### Step 1 — Admin Sign-In\n\nThe first screen asks an administrator to sign in with their email and password. This is on purpose: only an admin (or someone allowed to manage terminals) can pair a device, so a worker can't accidentally point a kiosk at the wrong team. A wrong password shows 'Invalid admin credentials'. A good sign-in loads the list of teams and moves on.\n\n### Step 2 — Name the Terminal & Choose a Team\n\nNow you give the kiosk an identity:\n\n- **Terminal Name** — a plain label for this station, like 'Weld Cell Kiosk' or 'Shipping Dock Tablet'. It's how the terminal shows up in the admin's terminal list. It's required.\n- **Team** — pick a team from the menu (each shows the team name and how many members it has), or click **Create New Team**, type a name, and it's created on the spot. The team you choose sets what the kiosk shows: its dashboard and worker list stick to that team.\n\nClick **Activate Terminal** to finish. The kiosk saves its pairing on the device, registers the terminal and team with the server, and then **signs the admin out** — on purpose, so the kiosk is left ready for workers, with nobody signed in.\n\n### What Pairing Does\n\nThe pairing is the kiosk's lasting identity. Each time it opens, it checks that pairing with the server:\n\n- **Still good** → the kiosk skips setup and goes straight to the team dashboard.\n- **Gone or turned off** (an admin removed or deactivated the terminal) → the saved pairing is cleared and the kiosk returns to Setup, ready to be paired again.\n\nBecause the pairing lives on the device, it's per-device and per-browser. Re-imaging the machine, switching browsers, or clearing the browser's data will mean pairing again. An admin can also turn off a terminal from the terminal list, which sends that device back into Setup the next time it opens.\n\n### Managing Terminals Later\n\nTerminals are listed and managed by an admin under the kiosk terminal settings. From there an admin can see which stations are paired and to which teams, and turn off a terminal that's been retired or moved. Turning it off doesn't touch the device — it just ends the pairing so the next open re-runs Setup.\n\n### Setup Covers Both Kiosks\n\nThe same pairing covers both kiosk screens. The **clock kiosk** runs setup directly. The **main shop floor display** also needs a paired terminal and team to show the right workers and jobs. Pair the device once and both are ready for the floor.","sections":[]}"""
