            Summary = "The dedicated clock-in/out kiosk: the team dashboard, the dual-scan flow (badge or job barcode in any order), PIN entry, the manual-login fallback, and ephemeral auto-logout.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 8,
            AppRoutes = """["/display/shop-floor/clock"]""",
            Tags = """["shop-floor","kiosk","clock","scan"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Using the Clock Kiosk\n\nThe Clock Kiosk is a focused, full-screen station for clocking in and out. It's simpler than the main shop floor display — no worker cards, no drag-and-drop — and it's built around one scan box, so a badge reader drives the whole thing. Once the device is paired (see 'Setting Up a Shop Floor Kiosk'), the kiosk opens straight to its team dashboard.\n\n### The Team Dashboard\n\nThe header shows the kiosk's team (a color dot and the team name), a live clock and date, and a search box. A strip across the top gives an at-a-glance team picture: how many workers are working, on break, and off, plus active jobs, jobs done today, and an overdue count (shown only when something's overdue). Below that, the dashboard lists the team's workers grouped by status — working, on break, and clocked out — and the team's active jobs. It refreshes on its own every few seconds.\n\n### Scan a Badge or a Job\n\nWhat sets the clock kiosk apart is that it takes **two kinds of scan, in either order**. At the bottom of the dashboard is a scan box that's always ready. When you scan something, the kiosk sorts it out:\n\n- **A worker badge** → goes straight to the PIN screen.\n- **A job barcode** → the kiosk shows the job (number, title, stage) and says 'Scan your badge to continue'. So a worker can scan the job they're about to work on first, then their badge — the clock entry ties to that job. Order doesn't matter: badge-then-job or job-then-badge both work.\n- **Something it can't read** → a 'scan not recognized' message on the dashboard.\n\nIf the kiosk can't tell what a scan is, it treats it as a badge and shows the PIN screen anyway, so a worker is never stuck.\n\n### PIN Entry\n\nAfter a badge is recognized, the worker types their number PIN (at least 4 digits, up to 8). Any job they scanned first shows on the PIN card as a reminder. Submitting signs them in with badge and PIN. A wrong badge or PIN shows 'Invalid badge or PIN' and lets them try again; **Back** returns to the dashboard.\n\n### Manual Sign-In\n\nSometimes there's no working badge — a new hire whose card hasn't printed, a damaged badge, a visitor covering a shift. The **Clock In Manually** button opens an email-and-password sign-in. This uses the regular password (not the kiosk PIN) and lands the worker on the same clock screen as a good scan. A wrong password shows 'Invalid credentials'.\n\n### The Clock Screen\n\nOnce signed in (by scan and PIN or by manual sign-in), the worker sees the clock buttons that fit their status — Clock In when they're out, Clock Out, Break, or Lunch when they're in, plus any custom ones your site sets up. Each button has its own icon and color. If a job was scanned, it shows as a banner so the worker can confirm they're clocking against the right one. Tapping a button records the clock entry.\n\n### One Action, Then Signed Out\n\nLike the main display, the clock kiosk signs you in for one action at a time — there's no lasting login. The moment a clock action goes through, the kiosk signs the worker out, refreshes, and returns to the team dashboard for the next person. And if someone walks away mid-way, a 30-second timer signs them out on its own (any button press starts it over), so the kiosk never sits open on someone's account. Backing out of the PIN, scanned-job, or manual sign-in screens does the same and returns to the dashboard.","sections":[]}"""
